div.p:
When describing an addition, please provide if possible:


language;

hand (by
                            a recent/old hand, by the same hand as that of the main text,
                            by the same hand as that of another addition, etc.); "in a
                            secondary hand" should be avoided: it is obvious;

ink (in
                            recent ink, hardly legible because of the faded ink, etc.).

readability (hardly readable, washed/scratched out etc.);

whether the addition is rhymed.

Under  Varia or extra, we list the following phenomena, which simply concern the
                    copying process or are more trivial than
                    additiones:


the title of
  the work written on the front board or cover, sometimes with
  blue or black paint or ink;

the midpoint in the "Psalms of
  David" (in Ps. 77, after the word በደመና፡);

the presence
  of stamps of the owning repository;

part of the line is
  taken up or taken down (e.g., in the Psalters);

glosses written in the margins;

the so-called
 tamallas-sign, in the shape
 of a cross (as +) or two perpendicular lines (as ┴ or├),
 indicating the place where the omissions (written in the upper
 or lower margin) belong;

omitted letters, words,
lines or passages inserted interlineally, in the margins, at
the beginning/end of the line ;

erasures;

corrections written over erasures, in the main hand or in a
    later recent hand;

erasures marked with thin black
    and red lines;

corrections immediately indicated by
the scribe through thin series of dashes above and below the
letters or the words;

spaces for rubricated names
    left unfilled;

unfilled spaces marked with thin
    black lines;

cues for the rubricator written in the
    margin or in the interocolumn (e.g., small digits);

erased names or names secondarily written over erased names
    (typically in the supplication formulas);

the
scribe reduced the size of his handwriting to accommodate the
end of the line;

the scribe used compressed script
("compressed" means two lines in a space originally
meant for one single line), often to accommodate lines written
over erasure;

monthly or daily readings are usually
indicated by writing the names of the months and weekdays in
the upper margin of the folio, sometimes within frames;

pen
trials, notes crudely written in pencil or pen;

scribbles and doodles.
